data.content:
## What happened

This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. In .NET 10, new implicit span conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees **cannot represent** span-based method calls, so it throws at runtime.

## Fix

Force the call to bind to the `IEnumerable<T>` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three prevent the compiler from choosing the span overload. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays (now resolves to the in-place `Span` extension instead of `Enumerable.Reverse`).
